Security Requirement

Any privileged identity access must require MFA, regardless of location, device, or application.

Design Decisions 
Roles included

Global Administrator
Privileged Role Administrator
Security Administrator
Conditional Access Administrator
Authentication Administrator
(These cover PIM‑eligible and active roles automatically)

Subscription Owners
Handled via group‑based assignment:

Azure AD group: AZ-Subscription-Owners
Subscription RBAC Owner assigned via group
Group included in Conditional Access

Key principles

All cloud apps (not just Azure Portal)
No trusted location exclusions
Break‑glass accounts excluded
Start in Report‑only, then enforce


Before deploying either policy:
Required Entra ID role
You must be one of: Global Administrator, Conditional Access Administrator, Security Administrator
Create break‑glass account
Create AZ-Subscription-Owners group
Add subscription owners to group


Go to https://aka.ms/ge

Sign in with admin account
Set API version to v1.0
Click Modify permissions
Add and Consent to: Policy.ReadWrite.ConditionalAccess

Deploy via Graph
1. HTTP Method: POST
2. Endpoint: https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/identity/conditionalAccess/policies
3. JSON
4. CA policy created and visible in Entra Admin Center → Conditional Access (MFA simulated (no impact yet))

Validate

Azure AD → Sign‑in logs
Filter: Report‑only
Confirm MFA would be required

Finally Enforce ("state": "enabled")

Recommended lifecycle (Microsoft best practice)

Report‑only → 24–72 hours
Review Sign‑in Logs → “Report‑only”
Confirm MFA would succeed
Switch to enabled
In production, no legitimate admin CA policy should skip report‑only.

MFA intentionally disabled for 1 Break-glass user account (Min 1 and Max 2)


Via Portal:
===========

Path:
Microsoft Entra Admin Center
→ Protection
→ Conditional Access
→ New policy

What you can do in the portal

Target directory roles (Global Admin, etc.)
Include a group for Subscription Owners
Exclude break‑glass accounts
Require MFA
Set Report‑only or Enabled
